def get_subnet_weight(subnet_id):

# Returns the wallet's uid if it is registered on subnet, None if it isn't
def get_wallet_uid(hotkey, subnet_id):
    metagraph = subtensor.metagraph(subnet_id)
    axons = metagraph.axons
    uid = 0
    for axon in axons:

    metagraph = subtensor.metagraph(subnet_id)
    subnet_tao_per_day = get_subnet_weight(subnet_id)*7200
    incentives = metagraph.incentive.tolist()
    wallet_uid = get_wallet_uid(hotkey, subnet_id)
    wallet_incentive = incentives[wallet_uid]

If you are asking what the risks are to delegators if a validator is deregistered, or goes offline, or whether a validator operator can run away with your staked TAO: when you delegate to a validator, the validator is using your Tao to earn additional rewards and increase its position on the network.  The validator does not have access to your staked Tao and cannot take them, even if operating maliciously: your Tao is never forfeited nor are the additional gains you receive in the form of Tao at a rate of 82% of that validator’s rate. 

If the validator goes down, both you and the validator stop earning Tao. At that point, you can unstake your Tao (including any gains you earned while validator was running) and the validator keeps their portion of the additional gains from your your Tao (18%).  Your original stake and rewards earned are never in jeopardy and can be unstaked at any time. 

If everyone else suddenly unstaked from a validator you're staked to and it lost its vpermit, you'd simply stop earning rewards.  If it still had vpermit, you'd still receive rewards -- but obviously they'd be much reduced, since dividends to a validator are related to their total stake. : )
